I am reading an excerpt from Morita's book. The story is that if you have a connection $
abla$ on a vector bundle $E$ over some manifold $M$ and a function $M_n(\mathbb{R})	o \mathbb{R}$ which is a homogeneous polynomial invariant under conjugation, then you obtain a form on $M$ by applying $f$ to the curvature matrix $\Omega$. What needs to be shown is that $f(\Omega)$ is a closed form, and that $[f(\Omega)]$ doesn't depend on the connection you started with. The second part is what I'm having trouble with. What Morita does is suppose we are given connections $
abla^0$ and $
abla^1$ on $E$. Consider the bundle $E	imes\mathbb{R}	o M	imes\mathbb{R}$ and define a connection $	ilde{
abla}$ on $E	imes \mathbb{R}$ in the following way. Suppose $s$ is a section of $E	imes\mathbb{R}$ which is independent of $t$ (that is, $s(p,t) = s(p,t')$ for all $t, t'$). Then define $	ilde{
abla}_{ rac{\partial}{\partial t}} s = 0$ and  $$ 	ilde{
abla}_X s = (1-t)
abla_X^0 s + t
abla_X^1 s  $$ for $X\in T_{(p,t)}(M	imes\mathbb{R})$. I understand that every vector field on $M	imes \mathbb{R}$ can be written as a linear combination with function coefficients of $ rac{\partial}{\partial t}$ and vector fields which are tangent to $M	imes \{t\}$. Morita says that also every section of $E	imes \mathbb{R}$ can be written as a linear combination with function coefficients of sections which are independent of $t$. I don't see why this is true. Moreover, aren't you supposed to be feeding connections vector fields and not tangent vectors? Is the point here that a vector field on $M	imes\mathbb{R}$ which is tangent to $M	imes \{t\}$ can be considered as a vector field on $M$?

